{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585935"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:22:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:22:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15038"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15038","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15038"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.71,0.05,0.05,0.05,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7726"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75831"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7726","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7726"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15038"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61344"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"},{"type":"tags","id":"8124"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18873"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18875"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75831"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDrug-induced hypersensitivity interstitial nephritis typically develops 7-14 days after starting the causative medication. While a classic triad exists of fever, rash and eosinophilia, this is not always present.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications is most commonly associated with drug-induced interstitial nephritis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Beta-lactam antibiotics","Thiazide diuretics","Beta blockers","Calcium channel blockers","Angiotensin converting enzyme inhibitors"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDrug-induced interstitial nephritis is a hypersensitivity reaction that can occur with various medications. \u003Cstrong\u003EBeta-lactam antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E (including penicillins and cephalosporins) are the most common culprits. While \u003Cstrong\u003Ethiazide diuretics\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Ebeta blockers\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalcium channel blockers\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Eangiotensin converting enzyme inhibitors\u003C/strong\u003E can cause various kidney problems, they rarely cause hypersensitivity interstitial nephritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther common causes include non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs and proton pump inhibitors. The condition is characterised by inflammatory infiltrates in the kidney interstitium, leading to acute kidney injury. Though there\u0027s a classic triad of fever, rash and eosinophilia, this only shows up in about 10% of cases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Beta-lactam antibiotics are the most common cause of drug-induced interstitial nephritis, followed by proton pump inhibitors and non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs","The classic triad of drug-induced interstitial nephritis includes fever, rash, and eosinophilia, though this occurs in only 10% of cases","Symptoms typically develop 7-14 days after starting the causative medication"],"references":["Praga M, Gonz\u00e1lez E. Acute interstitial nephritis. Kidney Int. 2010 Jun;77(11):956-61. doi: 10.1038/ki.2010.89. Epub 2010 Mar 24. PMID: 20336051.","Caravaca-Font\u00e1n F, Fern\u00e1ndez-Ju\u00e1rez G, Praga M. Acute kidney injury in interstitial nephritis. Curr Opin Crit Care. 2019 Dec;25(6):558-564. doi: 10.1097/MCC.0000000000000654. PMID: 31503026.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61344"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15038"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61344"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-31T22:02:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-31T22:15:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7726"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75831"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4933"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urinary","synonyms":[],"description":null,"p